    <div class="ctx_content p402_premium">
	<!-- C-ON-TEXT_CONTENT_START -->
    <!-- content -->
        <div class="clearfix hR new-style">
            <!-- MAINIMAGE --><section class="photo changeSpace"><p class="withoutCaption"><img src="http://cdn.images.express.co.uk/img/dynamic/41/590x/Calais-migrants-595405.jpg" alt="Calais migrants climbing fence"><meta itemprop="image" content="http://cdn.images.express.co.uk/img/dynamic/41/590x/Calais-migrants-595405.jpg"><span class="photo-caption nointellitxt ctx_blocked defaultLeft">PA</span></p><span class="newsCaption">The Calais crisis is hurting the economy</span></section><!-- ENDMAINIMAGE --><section class="text-description"><p>It is astonishing that there are scenes reminiscent of a war zone on our border with thousands of migrants trying to break into the country, and yet the Government has failed to intervene with any sense of purpose.</p><p>Yesterday the French strikers were back contributing to the mayhem.</p><p>Travellers are still beset with disruption and lorry drivers are running a gauntlet of fear.</p><p>And the Prime Minister has admitted that this situation could last all summer.</p><p>Some new fencing is simply not good enough.</p><p>It would be foolishly optimistic to expect these tenacious migrants to be foiled by something so simple, especially when they continue to overwhelm the police.</p><p>Similarly, plans to deploy more sniffer dogs this side of the border are welcome but inadequate when so many are pouring across.</p><p>These half-hearted measures are also unlikely to make it significantly safer and easier for legal travellers to make it through Calais.</p><p>This crisis is hurting the economy and putting people&rsquo;s safety at risk.</p><p>It needs to be dealt with urgently.</p></section><section class="photo changeSpace"><p class="withoutCaption"><img src="http://cdn.images.express.co.uk/img/dynamic/41/590x/secondary/Nicola-Sturgeon-325837.jpg" alt="SNP's Nicola Sturgeon" title="SNP's Nicola Sturgeon" /><span class="photo-caption defaultLeft">GETTY</span></p><span class="newsCaption">The SNP speaks only for a tiny portion of the UK population</span></section><section class="text-description"><h3>SNP&rsquo;s arrogant bullying</h3><p>WITH their socialism, their moaning about the Tories and their anti-Westminster rhetoric the SNP have managed to win huge support among Scots.</p><p>But we should never forget what motivates those at the top of the party.</p><p>Whatever else they claim to care about, all they are really committed to is driving a wedge between Scotland and the rest of Britain.</p><p>Nicola Sturgeon says that David Cameron can&rsquo;t stand in the way of another independence referendum.</p><p>This is breathtaking arrogance less than a year since the Scottish people voted to remain part of the United Kingdom.</p><p>Despite the SNP&rsquo;s inflated sense of their own importance the party speaks for only a tiny proportion of the UK population.</p><p>They cannot expect to bully the Prime Minister into indulging their juvenile demands.</p></section><section class="photo changeSpace"><p class="withoutCaption"><img src="http://cdn.images.express.co.uk/img/dynamic/41/590x/secondary/Bored-child-325839.jpg" alt="Child looking bored" title="Child looking bored" /><span class="photo-caption defaultLeft">GETTY</span></p><span class="newsCaption">Boredom can be character building for children</span></section><section class="text-description"><h3>We&rsquo;re all bored sometimes</h3><p>TODAY is the day that most parents run out of ways to keep their children entertained, according to a new report.</p><p>If you&rsquo;re one of them it&rsquo;s probably best not to worry.</p><p>Back in the day it was never a parent&rsquo;s job to provide amusement for the whole summer, and why should it be? A bit of boredom is a fact of life.</p><p>It&rsquo;s character building for children to experience it.</p></section><section class="box related-articles clear">
